[As Dr. Pyke points out, individuals infected with JE virus and returning to Australia from Bali, Indonesia have appeared before, as recently as 2018 (see Japanese encephalitis - Indonesia: (BA,SW) 20181108.6132871).

The very thorough and remarkably rapid laboratory testing established the JE virus etiology in this case. It is interesting that the sequences of their isolate matched 99.23% with the JEV Bali 2017 JE virus sequence. The current condition of the patient is not mentioned but obviously is a clinical case of JE. It will be interesting to learn whether JE vaccination is recommended for visitors to Bali, a popular tourist destination, and whether tourists will heed vaccination advice, given that JE cases are sporadic and less than 1% of JE virus infected individuals develop clinical illness.

The USA CDC notes that among patients who develop encephalitis, 20%-30% die. Although some symptoms improve after the acute illness, 30%-50% of survivors continue to have neurologic, cognitive, or psychiatric symptoms (see https://www.cdc.gov/japaneseencephalitis/symptoms/index.html). - Mod.TY

